			"html": "<p>Creating Aliases on a Mac is an easy thing to do &#x26; can save a lot of time. When working in Terminal or another command line app, you may want to set up an alias to make your workflows easier.\n{: .first-paragraph}</p>\n<p>To do this you’ll want to set up a <code class=\"language-text\">.bash_profile</code>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Run <code class=\"language-text\">vi ~/.bash_profile</code> in your command line app of choice, or [text editor of choice] ~/.bash_profile</li>\n<li>This will open up your <code class=\"language-text\">bash profile</code> in <code class=\"language-text\">vi</code> or your <code class=\"language-text\">text editor</code> to be edited</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you’d like to use a text editor but don’t have one that opens instead of <code class=\"language-text\">vi</code> checkout this <a href=\"//help.github.com/articles/associating-text-editors-with-git/\">post</a></p>\n<p>Here’s a look at part of my <code class=\"language-text\">.bash_profile</code>:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\">\n      <pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"># -------\n# mySQL\n# -------\nexport PATH=/usr/local/mysql/bin:$PATH\n\n# -------\n# host setups\n# -------\nalias hosts=&quot;sublime /etc/hosts&quot;\nalias vhosts=&quot;sublime /etc/apache2/vhosts&quot;</code></pre>\n      </div>",
